  "interpretation": {
    "supported_claim": "On this machine and the recorded one-million-cell level-1 isolated writer workloads, 512 KiB reduced combined target-entry median by 4.30% for numeric, 5.06% for mixed-inline and 0.85% for formula versus 1 MiB, while reducing median maximum writer-call wall time by 41.65%-53.26% and process peak working set by about 0.99 MiB.",
    "order_limit": "Numeric and mixed-inline improved in both ascending and descending buffer orders. Formula improved by 2.76% in ascending order and regressed by 0.43% in descending order, so no universal per-workload throughput improvement is claimed.",
    "larger_buffer_limit": "The 2 MiB and 4 MiB cases did not provide stable cross-workload target-entry gains and increased process peak working set to roughly 9.39 MiB and 13.39 MiB in the isolated process.",
    "patch_confirmation": "Patch schema v15/matrix v9 confirmed the selected 512 KiB input peak, 1 MiB two-buffer prefetch peak, CRC reuse, bounded call traffic and successful openpyxl validation for numeric, mixed-inline and formula-plus-external-hyperlink upsert outputs.",
    "next_hotspot": "The remaining measured cost is synchronous minizip DEFLATE writer work. Next profiling should distinguish minizip internal output-buffer/backend bookkeeping from zlib compression and scheduler noise before considering backend or concurrency changes."
  },
  "scope": "Single Windows/MSVC machine, deterministic one-million-cell worksheet payloads, production minizip-ng, DEFLATE level 1 and the recorded buffer sweep. This does not establish cross-machine, arbitrary-workbook, Office, pure-encoder, full-feature or OpenXLSX-superiority claims."
